## Why This Is Asked
Explores a real-world need for runtime-extensible security policies in service meshes, balancing safety and agility.

## Key Concepts
- Policy interface and evaluation contract
- Runtime plugin/registry for hot-swapping
- Request flow with gate, short-circuiting, and auditing
- Concurrency-safe updates and observability

## Code Example
```javascript
interface Policy {
  id: string
  name: string
  evaluate(req: any): boolean
}

class PolicyRegistry {
  private policies = new Map<string, Policy>()
  register(p: Policy) { this.policies.set(p.id, p) }
  evaluateAll(req: any): boolean {
    for (const p of this.policies.values()) if (!p.evaluate(req)) return false
    return true
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you handle conflicting policies and priority rules?
- How would you test hot-swapping without affecting in-flight requests?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design extensible runtime components with loose coupling. Evaluates understanding of pluggable architectures and vendor-agnostic integration patterns for enterprise systems.

## Key Concepts
- Strategy pattern for pluggable providers
- Registry/factory for dynamic loading
- Token caching and refresh orchestration
- Runtime extension via dynamic imports
- Interface segregation for minimal contracts

## Code Example
```javascript
// Minimal interface sketch (not full implementation)
interface AuthProvider {
  authenticate(req: any): Promise<Claims>
  refresh(token: string): Promise<Claims>
}

class Registry {
  private map = new Map<string, () => AuthProvider>()

  register(name: string, factory: () => AuthProvider) {
    this.map.set(name, factory)
  }

  get(name: string): AuthProvider {
    const factory = this.map.get(name)
    if (!factory) throw new Error(`Provider ${name} not found`)
    return factory()
  }
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests the ability to design an extensible, runtime-configurable pipeline using classic design patterns, with attention to non-blocking dispatch and clear separation of concerns.

## Key Concepts

- Strategy pattern for formatters and sinks
- Registry for runtime extension points
- Async broadcasting to sinks with fault tolerance

## Code Example

```javascript
interface LogRecord { level: string; message: string; timestamp: number; meta?: any; }
interface Formatter { format(rec: LogRecord): string; }
interface Sink { log(message: string): Promise<void>; }

class Registry<T> {
  private map = new Map<string, T>();
  register(name: string, item: T) { this.map.set(name, item); }
  get(name: string): T | undefined { return this.map.get(name); }
}

class Logger {
  private formatters = new Registry<Formatter>();
  private sinks = new Registry<Sink[]>();

  logRecord(rec: LogRecord) {
    const formatter = this.formatters.get("default");
    const msg = (formatter?.format(rec) ?? `${rec.timestamp} ${rec.level}: ${rec.message}`);
    const sinks = this.sinks.get("default") ?? [];
    Promise.all(sinks.map(s => s.log(msg))).catch(() => {});
  }

  registerFormatter(name: string, f: Formatter) { this.formatters.register(name, f); }
  registerSink(name: string, s: Sink) {
    const arr = this.sinks.get(name) ?? [];
    arr.push(s);
    this.sinks.register(name, arr);
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you handle backpressure if sinks become slow or fail repeatedly?
- How would you hot-swap formatters without losing logs during a switch?

## Why This Is Asked

This task tests designing a runtime-extensible routing layer that remains decoupled from concrete backends, enabling hot-swapping adapters and policies in high-throughput streaming pipelines applicable to modern platforms.

## Key Concepts

- Runtime extensibility via registries and adapters
- Policy-driven routing for load balancing and backpressure
- Exactly-once or at-least-once delivery guarantees with idempotency

## Code Example

```javascript
interface BackendAdapter {
  enqueue(task: any): Promise<void>;
  ack(id: string): Promise<void>;
}
class BackendRegistry {
  private map = new Map<string, BackendAdapter>();
  register(name: string, adapter: BackendAdapter) { this.map.set(name, adapter); }
  get(name: string): BackendAdapter { return this.map.get(name)!; }
}
class Router {
  constructor(private registry: BackendRegistry, private routeFn: (task: any) => string) {}
  async route(task: any) {
    const backendName = this.routeFn(task);
    const adapter = this.registry.get(backendName);
    return adapter.enqueue(task);
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you implement backpressure signals across multiple backends?
- What are the trade-offs of at-least-once vs exactly-once in this design?

