## Why This Is Asked
Assesses ability to design extensible behavior with minimal core changes; tests understanding of runtime extensibility and basic concurrency implications in rate limiting.

## Key Concepts
- Strategy pattern for interchangeable policies
- Plugin/registry to add new policies without touching core
- Per-user-per-endpoint scoping and idempotent canDeliver
- Lightweight state handling; consider clock/timing

## Code Example
```javascript
interface RatePolicy {
  canDeliver(userId: string, endpoint: string, now: number, n?: number): boolean;
}
class TokenBucketPolicy implements RatePolicy { /*...*/ }
class FixedWindowPolicy implements RatePolicy { /*...*/ }
class SlidingWindowPolicy implements RatePolicy { /*...*/ }

class PolicyRegistry {
  private map = new Map<string, () => RatePolicy>();
  register(name: string, maker: () => RatePolicy) { this.map.set(name, maker); }
  create(name: string): RatePolicy | undefined { const m = this.map.get(name); return m ? m() : undefined; }
}

class RateLimiter {
  constructor(private registry: PolicyRegistry) {}
  allow(userId: string, endpoint: string, policyName: string, n: number = 1): boolean {
    const policy = this.registry.create(policyName);
    if (!policy) throw new Error(`Unknown policy: ${policyName}`);
    return policy.canDeliver(userId, endpoint, Date.now(), n);
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you unit-test each policy in isolation?
- How would you scale state across multiple instances?

