## Why This Is Asked
This question assesses the ability to design runtime-extensible components, balancing modularity with operational safety in distributed, high-throughput systems.

## Key Concepts
- Strategy pattern: decouples limiter logic from engine
- Registry: dynamic, runtime-extendable mapping
- Factory: safe instance creation
- Hot swapping: registry updates without downtime
- Concurrency: thread-safe counters, lock-free where possible
- Distribution: config propagation via central store

## Code Example
```typescript
interface RateLimiter {
  tryAcquire(n: number): boolean
}

class TokenBucket implements RateLimiter {
  constructor(private capacity: number, private fillRate: number) {}
  tryAcquire(n: number): boolean { return true }
}
class LeakyBucket implements RateLimiter {
  constructor(private rate: number) {}
  tryAcquire(n: number): boolean { return true }
}
class SlidingWindow implements RateLimiter {
  constructor(private window: number) {}
  tryAcquire(n: number): boolean { return true }
}

type Factory = () => RateLimiter

class RateLimiterRegistry {
  private map = new Map<string, Factory>()
  register(name: string, factory: Factory) { this.map.set(name, factory) }
  create(name: string): RateLimiter {
    const f = this.map.get(name)
    if (!f) throw new Error(`Unknown rate limiter: ${name}`)
    return f()
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you ensure registry updates are atomic across a multi-process deployment?
- How would you test adding a new strategy without affecting live traffic?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a pluggable CLI core that remains simple yet extensible, a common pattern in large frontend and backend tools at scale.

## Key Concepts

- Plugin architecture
- Runtime dynamic imports
- Registry pattern
- Aliases and help output
- Robust error isolation for plugins

## Code Example

```typescript
export interface PluginCommand {
  name: string;
  description: string;
  execute(args: string[]): Promise<number>;
}

export class CommandRegistry {
  private commands = new Map<string, PluginCommand>();
  private aliases = new Map<string, string>();

  async load(name: string, path: string): Promise<void> {
    const mod = await import(path);
    const cmd: PluginCommand = mod.default ?? mod;
    this.commands.set(name, cmd);
  }

  addAlias(alias: string, name: string) {
    this.aliases.set(alias, name);
  }

  async execute(name: string, args: string[]): Promise<number> {
    const actual = this.aliases.get(name) ?? name;
    const cmd = this.commands.get(actual);
    if (!cmd) throw new Error(`Unknown command: ${name}`);
    try {
      return await cmd.execute(args);
    } catch (e) {
      console.error(`Command failed: ${name}`, e);
      return 1;
    }
  }
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you sandbox plugins to prevent memory leaks or long-running tasks?
- How would you version and rollback plugin changes in a live CLI?
- How would you test command loading and error handling end-to-end?

## Why This Is Asked
This question evaluates your ability to design runtime-extensible components and reason about schema evolution challenges in streaming data pipelines.

## Key Concepts
- Strategy pattern for format abstraction
- Registry pattern for dynamic plugin discovery
- Lazy factory initialization for performance optimization
- Schema evolution strategies and backward compatibility
- Runtime configurability versus compile-time coupling trade-offs

## Code Example
```typescript
interface Serializer {
  serialize(obj: unknown): Buffer;
  deserialize(buf: Buffer): unknown;
}

type Factory = () => Serializer;

class SerializerRegistry {
  private serializers = new Map<string, Factory>();

  register(name: string, factory: Factory): void {
    this.serializers.set(name, factory);
  }

  get(name: string): Serializer {
    const factory = this.serializers.get(name);
    if (!factory) throw new Error(`Unknown serializer: ${name}`);
    return factory();
  }
}

// Usage
const registry = new SerializerRegistry();
registry.register('json', () => new JsonSerializer());
registry.register('avro', () => new AvroSerializer());
registry.register('protobuf', () => new ProtobufSerializer());

// Runtime switching
const format = getConfiguredFormat();
const serializer = registry.get(format);
```

## Schema Evolution & Backward Compatibility
- **Forward compatibility**: Consumers ignore unknown fields
- **Backward compatibility**: Producers provide default values for missing fields
- **Version negotiation**: Schema registries with compatibility checking
- **Migration strategies**: Dual-write during transitions

## Trade-offs
- **Performance**: Runtime resolution vs compile-time optimization
- **Memory**: Lazy loading vs eager initialization
- **Complexity**: Plugin architecture vs monolithic design
- **Type safety**: Dynamic serialization vs static guarantees

