## Why This Is Asked

This question evaluates your ability to design a runtime-extensible lifecycle system with clear separation of concerns, concurrency control, and robust error handling in a microservice context.

## Key Concepts

- **Plugin Architecture**: Registry pattern enabling runtime hook registration
- **Execution Ordering**: Dependency resolution and phase-based sequencing
- **Concurrency Control**: Distinguishing parallelizable hooks from sequential ones
- **Error Handling**: Aggregation strategies and graceful shutdown guarantees
- **Design Patterns**: Strategy vs Chain of Responsibility trade-offs

## Code Example

```typescript
interface LifecycleHook {
  name: string;
  phase: 'initialize' | 'start' | 'stop';
  parallelizable?: boolean;
  priority?: number;
  execute(ctx: LifecycleContext): Promise<void>;
}

interface LifecycleContext {
  components: Map<string, unknown>;
  errors: Error[];
}

class LifecycleHookRegistry {
  private hooks: LifecycleHook[] = [];

  register(hook: LifecycleHook): void {
    this.hooks.push(hook);
  }

  getByPhase(phase: string): LifecycleHook[] {
    return this.hooks.filter(h => h.phase === phase);
  }
}

class LifecycleManager {
  constructor(private registry: LifecycleHookRegistry) {}

  async executePhase(phase: 'initialize' | 'start' | 'stop'): Promise<void> {
    const hooks = this.registry.getByPhase(phase);
    const sequential = hooks.filter(h => !h.parallelizable);
    const parallel = hooks.filter(h => h.parallelizable);

    for (const hook of sequential) {
      await hook.execute({ components: new Map(), errors: [] });
    }

    await Promise.all(parallel.map(h => h.execute({ components: new Map(), errors: [] })));
  }
}

// Usage
const manager = new LifecycleManager(new LifecycleHookRegistry());
manager.registry.register({
  name: 'Warmup',
  phase: 'start',
  parallelizable: true,
  execute: async (ctx) => { /* warmup logic */ }
});
await manager.executePhase('start');
```

