**Design: Runtime-Extendable Policy Engine for Edge API Gateway**

A policy engine where each route can compose pluggable policies dynamically, with runtime registration without redeployment.

### Core Interfaces (TypeScript)

```typescript
type PolicyResult = 
  | { status: 'allowed'; metadata?: Record<string, unknown> }
  | { status: 'denied'; reason: string; code?: number };

interface Policy {
  name: string;
  evaluate(ctx: RequestContext): Promise<PolicyResult>;
  priority?: number; // Lower = evaluated first
}

interface PolicyRegistry {
  register(policy: Policy): void;
  get(name: string): Policy | undefined;
  list(): Policy[];
}

interface RoutePolicyConfig {
  routeId: string;
  policies: string[]; // Policy names in evaluation order
  isolationGroup?: string; // For shared state management
}
```

### Registry Implementation

```typescript
class DefaultPolicyRegistry implements PolicyRegistry {
  private policies = new Map<string, Policy>();

  register(policy: Policy): void {
    if (this.policies.has(policy.name)) {
      throw new Error(`Policy '${policy.name}' already registered`);
    }
    this.policies.set(policy.name, policy);
  }

  get(name: string): Policy | undefined {
    return this.policies.get(name);
  }

  list(): Policy[] {
    return Array.from(this.policies.values());
  }
}
```

### Policy Engine with Per-Route Composition

```typescript
class PolicyEngine {
  constructor(
    private registry: PolicyRegistry,
    private routeConfigs: Map<string, RoutePolicyConfig>
  ) {}

  async evaluate(routeId: string, req: RequestContext): Promise<PolicyResult> {
    const config = this.routeConfigs.get(routeId);
    if (!config) {
      return { status: 'allowed' };
    }

    for (const policyName of config.policies) {
      const policy = this.registry.get(policyName);
      if (!policy) {
        throw new Error(`Policy '${policyName}' not found for route '${routeId}'`);
      }

      const result = await policy.evaluate(req);

      if (result.status === 'denied') {
        return result; // Short-circuit on denial
      }
    }

    return { status: 'allowed' };
  }
}
```

### Usage Example

```typescript
// Initialize registry
const registry = new DefaultPolicyRegistry();

// Register built-in policies at runtime
registry.register({
  name: 'RateLimit',
  priority: 10,
  evaluate: async (ctx) => {
    const key = ctx.headers['x-api-key'] || ctx.ip;
    if (await isRateLimited(key)) {
      return { status: 'denied', reason: 'Rate limit exceeded', code: 429 };
    }
    return { status: 'allowed' };
  }
});

registry.register({
  name: 'AuthCheck',
  priority: 20,
  evaluate: async (ctx) => {
    const token = ctx.headers['authorization'];
    if (!token || !await validateToken(token)) {
      return { status: 'denied', reason: 'Unauthorized', code: 401 };
    }
    return { status: 'allowed' };
  }
});

registry.register({
  name: 'BotDetection',
  priority: 5,
  evaluate: async (ctx) => {
    const score = await detectBot(ctx.ip, ctx.headers);
    if (score > 0.8) {
      return { status: 'denied', reason: 'Bot detected', code: 403 };
    }
    return { status: 'allowed' };
  }
});

registry.register({
  name: 'ABRouting',
  priority: 100,
  evaluate: async (ctx) => {
    const bucket = hashUser(ctx.userId) % 100;
    ctx.metadata = { bucket };
    return { status: 'allowed' };
  }
});

// Configure per-route policies
const routeConfigs = new Map<string, RoutePolicyConfig>([
  ['/api/public', { routeId: '/api/public', policies: ['BotDetection'] }],
  ['/api/private', { routeId: '/api/private', policies: ['BotDetection', 'RateLimit', 'AuthCheck', 'ABRouting'] }],
]);

const engine = new PolicyEngine(registry, routeConfigs);

// Evaluate request
const result = await engine.evaluate('/api/private', { 
  headers: { 'authorization': 'Bearer token' },
  ip: '192.168.1.1',
  userId: 'user123'
});
```

### Handling Evaluation Order, Isolation, and Rollback

**Evaluation Order:**
- Use the explicit `priority` field on policies (lower values = evaluated first)
- BotDetection runs first to block malicious traffic early
- RateLimit executes before AuthCheck to prevent brute-force attacks without wasting auth resources
- ABRouting runs last after all security checks pass
- Routes define ordered policy lists; the engine executes them in sequence with short-circuit on denial

**Isolation:**
- Each policy receives a fresh `RequestContext` copy
- Use isolation groups for shared state (e.g., distributed rate limiting with Redis)
- Implement policy timeouts to prevent runaway evaluation
- Consider sandboxed policy execution in separate workers (optional enhancement)

**Rollback on Failure:**
- Wrap each `policy.evaluate()` in try-catch
- On exception: return `{ status: 'denied', reason: 'Policy failure: ' + error.message, code: 500 }`
- For stateful policies: implement compensating transactions or optimistic locking
- Audit log all policy decisions for debugging
- Circuit breaker pattern: if a policy fails repeatedly, skip it automatically

## Question

Design a runtime-extendable scheduling policy for a distributed job system. The core provides a WorkerQueue with enqueue, dequeue, and metrics. Allow registering new scheduling policies by name at runtime (e.g., FIFO, Priority, Aging) and apply a policy per queue without recompilation. Provide minimal interfaces, a registry, and a TypeScript usage example. Discuss fairness, starvation, and dynamic reload.

## Answer

### Minimal TypeScript Sketch

```typescript
interface Job {
  id: string;
  priority: number;
  createdAt: number;
}

interface SchedulingPolicy {
  name: string;
  nextIndex(queue: Job[]): number | null;
}

class PolicyRegistry {
  private policies = new Map<string, SchedulingPolicy>();

  register(name: string, policy: SchedulingPolicy): void {
    if (this.policies.has(name)) {
      throw new Error(`Policy '${name}' already registered`);
    }
    this.policies.set(name, policy);
  }

  get(name: string): SchedulingPolicy | undefined {
    return this.policies.get(name);
  }

  unregister(name: string): boolean {
    return this.policies.delete(name);
  }
}

class WorkerQueue {
  private jobs: Job[] = [];
  private policy: SchedulingPolicy;

  constructor(
    private name: string,
    private registry: PolicyRegistry,
    initialPolicy: string = 'FIFO'
  ) {
    this.setPolicy(initialPolicy);
  }

  setPolicy(name: string): void {
    const policy = this.registry.get(name);
    if (!policy) {
      throw new Error(`Unknown policy: ${name}`);
    }
    this.policy = policy;
  }

  enqueue(job: Job): void {
    this.jobs.push(job);
  }

  dequeue(): Job | null {
    const idx = this.policy.nextIndex(this.jobs);
    if (idx === null) return null;
    return this.jobs.splice(idx, 1)[0];
  }

  getMetrics() {
    return {
      length: this.jobs.length,
      policy: this.policy.name,
    };
  }
}

// Built-in policies
const FIFO: SchedulingPolicy = {
  name: 'FIFO',
  nextIndex: (queue) => queue.length > 0 ? 0 : null,
};

const Priority: SchedulingPolicy = {
  name: 'Priority',
  nextIndex: (queue) => {
    if (queue.length === 0) return null;
    let maxIdx = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i < queue.length; i++) {
      if (queue[i].priority > queue[maxIdx].priority) maxIdx = i;
    }
    return maxIdx;
  },
};

const Aging: SchedulingPolicy = {
  name: 'Aging',
  nextIndex: (queue) => {
    if (queue.length === 0) return null;
    const now = Date.now();
    let oldest = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i < queue.length; i++) {
      const waitA = now - queue[i].createdAt;
      const waitB = now - queue[oldest].createdAt;
      if (waitA > waitB) oldest = i;
    }
    return oldest;
  },
};
```

### Usage Example

```typescript
const registry = new PolicyRegistry();
registry.register('FIFO', FIFO);
registry.register('Priority', Priority);
registry.register('Aging', Aging);

const queue = new WorkerQueue('workers', registry, 'Priority');
queue.enqueue({ id: 'job1', priority: 1, createdAt: Date.now() });
queue.enqueue({ id: 'job2', priority: 10, createdAt: Date.now() });
queue.enqueue({ id: 'job3', priority: 5, createdAt: Date.now() });

console.log(queue.dequeue()?.id); // 'job2' (highest priority)

queue.setPolicy('FIFO');
console.log(queue.dequeue()?.id); // 'job1' (first in)

queue.setPolicy('Aging');
console.log(queue.dequeue()?.id); // 'job3' (oldest waiting)
```

