## Code Example
```typescript
type NextFn = () => Promise<void>;

interface Middleware {
  name: string;
  handle(ctx: Context, next: NextFn): Promise<void>;
}

class MiddlewareRegistry {
  private middleware = new Map<string, Middleware>();

  register(name: string, factory: () => Middleware): void {
    this.middleware.set(name, factory());
  }

  get(name: string): Middleware | undefined {
    return this.middleware.get(name);
  }

  createPipeline(names: string[]): Middleware {
    const chain = names.map(n => this.middleware.get(n)).filter(Boolean);
    return {
      name: 'pipeline',
      async handle(ctx, next) {
        let idx = 0;
        const run = async (): Promise<void> {
          if (idx < chain.length) {
            await chain[idx++].handle(ctx, run);
          } else {
            await next();
          }
        }
        await run();
      }
    };
  }
}

// Usage
const registry = new MiddlewareRegistry();
registry.register('auth', () => ({ name: 'auth', async handle(ctx, next) { /* auth logic */ await next(); } }));
registry.register('logging', () => ({ name: 'logging', async handle(ctx, next) { /* logging */ await next(); } }));

const pipeline = registry.createPipeline(['auth', 'logging']);
await pipeline.handle(requestContext, () => handleRequest(requestContext));
```

## Trade-offs: Pipeline vs Chain of Responsibility

| Aspect | Pipeline | Chain of Responsibility |
|--------|----------|------------------------|
| **Control Flow** | Centralized composition; executor controls ordering | Decentralized; each handler decides whether to pass on |
| **Flexibility** | Easier to reorder, split, or reuse stages | More dynamic routing decisions at each node |
| **Error Handling** | Simpler to implement centralized error boundaries | Errors must propagate explicitly through handlers |
| **Debugging** | Clear execution path through pipeline | Harder to trace; handlers may skip chain |
| **Parallelization** | Natural fit for parallel branches in some implementations | Less suited; handlers typically execute sequentially |

**When to prefer Pipeline**: Fixed ordering, clear composition, easy configuration per endpoint.

**When to prefer Chain of Responsibility**: Dynamic routing, conditional processing, when handlers need autonomy over flow control.

