Use a Chain of Responsibility pattern with a per-tenant policy chain built from a registry of PolicyHandlers. Each handler implements `apply(req, ctx, next)` and returns a Promise. The chain is built from tenant-specific policy registrations, executed in defined order with proper isolation and error handling.

```typescript
interface PolicyContext {
  tenantId: string;
  request: any;
  metadata: Record<string, any>;
}

interface Policy {
  name: string;
  apply(req: any, ctx: PolicyContext, next: () => Promise<any>): Promise<any>;
}

class PolicyRegistry {
  private policies = new Map<string, () => Policy>();

  register(name: string, factory: () => Policy): void {
    this.policies.set(name, factory);
  }

  create(name: string): Policy {
    const factory = this.policies.get(name);
    if (!factory) throw new Error(`Policy '${name}' not registered`);
    return factory();
  }

  list(): string[] {
    return [...this.policies.keys()];
  }
}

class TenantPipeline {
  private chain: Policy[] = [];
  private registry: PolicyRegistry;

  constructor(registry: PolicyRegistry) {
    this.registry = registry;
  }

  configure(policyNames: string[]): void {
    this.chain = policyNames.map(name => this.registry.create(name));
  }

  async execute(req: any, ctx: PolicyContext): Promise<any> {
    let idx = 0;
    const next = async (): Promise<any> => {
      if (idx >= this.chain.length) return;
      const policy = this.chain[idx++];
      return policy.apply(req, ctx, next);
    };
    return next();
  }
}

// Usage:
const registry = new PolicyRegistry();
registry.register('RateLimit', () => new RateLimitPolicy());
registry.register('AuthCheck', () => new AuthCheckPolicy());
registry.register('AuditLog', () => new AuditLogPolicy());

const tenantA = new TenantPipeline(registry);
tenantA.configure(['RateLimit', 'AuthCheck', 'AuditLog']);

const ctx: PolicyContext = { tenantId: 'tenant-a', request: req, metadata: {} };
await tenantA.execute(req, ctx);
```

**Per-tenant isolation**: Each `TenantPipeline` instance maintains its own chain, and tenant context is injected via `PolicyContext`, ensuring policies operate on isolated data.

**Safe failure handling**: Wrap `policy.apply()` in try-catch with tenant-scoped fallback responses. Implement circuit breakers for downstream policy failures to prevent cascading errors across tenant boundaries."

