Use a Pipeline pattern with a central Registry. Define a `Transformer` interface with a `name` and `transform` method, and a `Registry` class to register and retrieve transformers by name. The core builds an ordered pipeline from registered transformers and executes them sequentially, catching errors per stage to ensure a failing transformer doesn't crash the pipeline.

```typescript
interface Transformer {
  name: string;
  transform(input: string): string;
}

class Registry {
  private map = new Map<string, Transformer>();
  register(t: Transformer): void { this.map.set(t.name, t); }
  get(name: string): Transformer | undefined { return this.map.get(name); }
}

class Pipeline {
  constructor(private registry: Registry) {}
  execute(input: string, order: string[]): string {
    return order.reduce((acc, name) => {
      const transformer = this.registry.get(name);
      return transformer ? transformer.transform(acc) : acc;
    }, input);
  }
}
```

**Usage example:**
```typescript
const registry = new Registry();
registry.register({ name: 'upper', transform: (s) => s.toUpperCase() });
registry.register({ name: 'prefix', transform: (s) => '>>> ' + s });

const pipeline = new Pipeline(registry);
const result = pipeline.execute('hello', ['prefix', 'upper']);
// Output: '>>> HELLO'
```

