## Why This Is Asked
Tests the ability to design a pluggable, runtime-extensible command system with safe isolation and atomic swaps—a common pattern in CLI tools and services.

## Key Concepts
- Plugin pattern and registry design
- Dynamic imports and module boundaries
- Atomic swaps and conflict resolution
- Isolation via workers or sandboxes
- Error handling and observability

## Code Example
```typescript
interface IPlugin {
  name: string;
  execute(args: string[]): Promise<void>;
}

class PluginRegistry {
  private registry = new Map<string, () => Promise<IPlugin>>();

  async register(path: string): Promise<void> {
    const mod = await import(path);
    const plugin = mod.default ?? mod;
    if (!this.isValidPlugin(plugin)) {
      throw new Error(`Invalid plugin at ${path}`);
    }
    this.registry.set(plugin.name, () => Promise.resolve(plugin));
  }

  private isValidPlugin(p: unknown): p is IPlugin {
    return typeof p === 'object' && p !== null &&
      typeof (p as IPlugin).name === 'string' &&
      typeof (p as IPlugin).execute === 'function';
  }

  async swap(path: string): Promise<void> {
    const mod = await import(path);
    const newPlugin = mod.default ?? mod;
    if (!this.isValidPlugin(newPlugin)) {
      throw new Error('Swap rejected: invalid plugin');
    }
    const existing = this.registry.get(newPlugin.name);
    if (!existing) {
      throw new Error(`Plugin '${newPlugin.name}' not registered`);
    }
    this.registry.set(newPlugin.name, () => Promise.resolve(newPlugin));
  }

  async execute(command: string, args: string[]): Promise<void> {
    const factory = this.registry.get(command);
    if (!factory) throw new Error(`Unknown command: ${command}`);
    const plugin = await factory();
    await plugin.execute(args);
  }
}
```

## Key Design Decisions
- **Interface validation**: Type guard ensures only valid plugins register
- **Atomic swap**: Swap completes before old plugin is removed—no downtime
- **Conflict resolution**: Attempting to swap a non-existent plugin throws; swap only succeeds if new plugin passes validation
- **Isolation**: For untrusted plugins, load in a Web Worker and communicate via `postMessage`
- **Factory pattern**: Deferred instantiation allows lazy loading and easy hot-swapping

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a runtime-extensible plugin system with concurrency considerations and clear trade-offs between design patterns.

## Key Concepts

- Strategy Pattern
- Registry/Service Locator
