## Why This Is Asked
This question assesses the ability to design a runtime-extensible component using well-established patterns—Strategy and Registry—and to reason about concurrency and distribution boundaries.

## Key Concepts
- **Strategy Pattern**: Enables pluggable eviction and serialization policies
- **Registry Pattern**: Allows dynamic extension by name without rebuilding
- **Thread-Safety**: Concurrent access with safe eviction operations
- **Per-Cache Isolation**: Independent policy and serializer instances per cache
- **Distributed Invalidation**: Cache coherence across nodes

## Code Example
```typescript
// Core interfaces
interface EvictionPolicy<K, V> {
  onAccess(key: K): void;
  selectEvictionCandidate(): K | null;
  onEvict(key: K): void;
}

interface Serializer<V> {
  serialize(value: V): Uint8Array;
  deserialize(data: Uint8Array): V;
}

interface Cache<K, V> {
  get(key: K): V | undefined;
  put(key: K, value: V): void;
  evict(key: K): void;
  clear(): void;
}

// Registry for runtime extension
class PolicyRegistry<K, V> {
  private policies = new Map<string, new () => EvictionPolicy<K, V>>();
  register(name: string, policy: new () => EvictionPolicy<K, V>): void {
    this.policies.set(name, policy);
  }
  resolve(name: string): EvictionPolicy<K, V> {
    const Policy = this.policies.get(name);
    if (!Policy) throw new Error(`Unknown policy: ${name}`);
    return new Policy();
  }
}

class SerializerRegistry<V> {
  private serializers = new Map<string, new () => Serializer<V>>();
  register(name: string, serializer: new () => Serializer<V>): void {
    this.serializers.set(name, serializer);
  }
  resolve(name: string): Serializer<V> {
    const Serializer = this.serializers.get(name);
    if (!Serializer) throw new Error(`Unknown serializer: ${name}`);
    return new Serializer();
  }
}

// Usage
const policyRegistry = new PolicyRegistry<string, User>();
policyRegistry.register('lru', LRUPolicy);
policyRegistry.register('lfu', LFUPolicy);

const serializerRegistry = new SerializerRegistry<User>();
serializerRegistry.register('json', JsonSerializer);
serializerRegistry.register('protobuf', ProtobufSerializer);

const cache = new DefaultCache<string, User>({
  policy: policyRegistry.resolve('lru'),
  serializer: serializerRegistry.resolve('json'),
  maxSize: 1000,
});
```

## Thread-Safety Considerations
- **Concurrent Map**: Use a thread-safe map (e.g., `ConcurrentHashMap` in Java, or mutexes in TypeScript/Node.js)
- **Atomic Operations**: Ensure get/put are atomic to prevent race conditions during eviction
- **Lock-Free Structures**: Consider lock-free data structures for high-throughput scenarios
- **Read/Write Locks**: Separate read and write locks to maximize concurrency

## Per-Cache Isolation
- Each cache instance maintains its own policy and serializer instances
- Policies operate on isolated internal state, preventing cross-cache interference
- Cache namespacing prevents key collisions in shared registries

## Distributed Invalidation
- **Write-Through/Write-Behind**: Propagate updates to a central store (Redis, Cassandra)
- **Pub/Sub Invalidation**: Subscribe to invalidation events on a message broker (Kafka, Redis Pub/Sub)
- **Versioning/Tombstones**: Track cache generations or deleted keys to prevent stale reads
- **Consistent Hashing**: Ensure requests route to nodes holding the cached entry for targeted invalidation

## Why This Is Asked
Explores runtime extensibility using the Decorator and Registry patterns in a practical CLI context.

## Key Concepts
- **Registry pattern**: Centralized storage for cross-cutting concerns
- **Decorator pattern**: Wraps commands in layers for logging, retry, and metrics
- **Per-command isolation**: Faults in one decorator don't cascade to others
- **Runtime composition**: Decorator chains are assembled at execution time, not compile time

## Code Example
```typescript
interface Command {
  execute(ctx: any): Promise<void>;
}

interface Decorator extends Command {
  setNext(cmd: Command): Command;
}

class DecoratorRegistry {
  private decorators: Decorator[] = [];

  register(decorator: Decorator) {
    this.decorators.push(decorator);
  }

  compose(cmd: Command): Command {
    return this.decorators.reduceRight(
      (inner, decorator) => decorator.setNext(inner),
      cmd
    );
  }
}

const registry = new DecoratorRegistry();

registry.register({
  setNext(cmd) {
    return {
      execute: async (ctx) => {
        console.log('Logging:', ctx);
        await cmd.execute(ctx);
      },
    };
  },
} as Decorator);

class CommandFactory {
  private commands = new Map<string, Command>();

  register(name: string, cmd: Command) {
    this.commands.set(name, registry.compose(cmd));
  }

  execute(name: string, ctx: any) {
    return this.commands.get(name)!.execute(ctx);
  }
}

const factory = new CommandFactory();
factory.register('deploy', {
  execute: async (ctx) => console.log('Deploying:', ctx),
});

factory.execute('deploy', { env: 'prod' });
```

## Key Takeaway
Adding a new cross-cutting concern requires only registering a new decorator—no modifications to existing commands or the factory.

