## Why This Is Asked
Tests expertise in runtime-extensible design, middleware patterns, and fault-tolerant execution. It also probes how to balance per-route specificity with global policy.

## Key Concepts
- Interceptor/middleware pattern and pipeline composition
- Runtime registries for pluggable behavior
- Per-route configuration versus global defaults
- Async handling, error isolation, and fault containment
- Context immutability for isolation

## Code Example
```typescript
interface Interceptor {
  handle(ctx: Context, next: () => Promise<Context>): Promise<Context>;
}
class Registry {
  private factories = new Map<string, () => Interceptor>();
  register(name: string, factory: () => Interceptor){ this.factories.set(name, factory); }
  create(name: string): Interceptor | undefined { const f = this.factories.get(name); return f ? f() : undefined; }
}
type Context = { route: string; user?: string; payload: any };
async function runPipeline(names: string[], ctx: Context, registry: Registry): Promise<Context> {
  const interceptors = names.map(n => registry.create(n)).filter((i): i is Interceptor => !!i);
  let idx = 0;
  const next = async (current: Context): Promise<Context> => {
    if (idx >= interceptors.length) return current;
    const interceptor = interceptors[idx++];
    try { return await interceptor!.handle(current, () => next(current)); }
    catch { return next(current); }
  };
  return next(ctx);
}
```

